  {
    "author": "Erik Nygren",
    "text": "<p>@Michael:  unfortunately not an RFC.  A concept proposed that boils down to doing something like<br>\n\"<a href=\"https://_NPNE4IG2GJ4VAL4DCHL64YSM5BII4A2X.cpe.local\">https://_NPNE4IG2GJ4VAL4DCHL64YSM5BII4A2X.cpe.local</a>\" where \"NPNE4IG2GJ4VAL4DCHL64YSM5BII4A2X\" is the key fingerprint.  In the ADD case this would bind the ADD response from network to the cert the CPE would use to authenticate but would also tie the cryptographic identity of the device to its HTTPS Origin to prevent leakage.  It means that you get locally unique private names.  (For DoT the alertative would be to otherwise include the public key fingerprint.)  Some of the ideas go back to David Mazieres' SFS which took a similar approach for naming entities.</p>",
    "topic": "ietf-119",
